          <td>
            <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="2">
              <tr> 
                <td class="chblue"><font class="h1font"> Fun Decks</font></td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="3"><tr><td><font class="bfont"><table width="100%" border="0" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0"><tr><td colspan="2"><font class="h1font">The Dreadful Fight</font></td></tr><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Rating</Font></TD><TD><table width='55' border='0' cellspacing='0' cellpadding='0'><tr><td background='/magination/gfx/5star.gif'><img src='/lotr/gfx/trans.gif' width='1' height='25'></td></tr></table><font size=1>(2.75)</font> | <A HREF="/magination/decks/decks.php?reviews=30045">Read Reviews</A></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Author</font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> <A HREF="http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=15004">Zach "Esper" Davis</A></FONT> <font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/magination/main/mpage.php?member=15004&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a></font></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Description</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> You know all those nasty tricks that video game bosses pull on you? It&#39;s time to pull them on your opponent!</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Submitted</Font></TD><TD><font class="bfont"> August 16, 2003</FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Cards</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> MAGI:<br />
<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(577)">Korremar</a> (starting: none)<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(516)">Gia</a> (starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(502)">Book of Ages</a>)<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(573)">Harror</a> (starting: <a href="javascript:card_browser(594)">Shryque</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(585)">Dark <a href="javascript:card_browser(325)">Ayebaw</a></a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(669)">Cataclysm</a>, <a href="javascript:card_browser(554)">Dream Rift</a>)<br />
<br />
CREATURES: <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(594)">Shryque</a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(682)">Chaos <a href="javascript:card_browser(403)">Plith</a></a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(591)">Koil</a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(585)">Dark <a href="javascript:card_browser(325)">Ayebaw</a></a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(580)">Black <a href="javascript:card_browser(464)">Agovo</a></a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(516)">Gia</a> Pet (3)<br />
18 Creatures <br />
<br />
SPELLS: <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(554)">Dream Rift</a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(790)">Beam of Light</a> (3)<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(556)">Gloom</a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(557)">Maelstrom</a> (2) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(669)">Cataclysm</a> (1) <br />
12 Spells <br />
<br />
RELICS: <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(886)">Secrets of the Book</a> (3) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(502)">Book of Ages</a> (2) <br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(575)">Warrada</a>&#39;s Ring (2)<br />
<a href="javascript:card_browser(529)">Abwyn&#39;s Quill</a> (2)<br />
Ritual Spear (1) <br />
10 Relics    </FONT></TD></TR><TR><TD WIDTH="10%" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="h2font"> Strategy</Font></TD><TD> </TD></TR><TR><TD COLSPAN="2" VALIGN="TOP"><font class="bfont"> NOTE: This is what I originally intended for my deck "The Decisive Battle". Somehow, some cards got left out, and one of the Magi got changed completely. That one is more competetive, this one is more fun. However, they both work, and swapping out some of the cards in either deck for some of the cards in the other is a viable strategy.<br />
<br /><br />
***EDIT INFO: It has been brought to my attention that Gia cannot play Relics other than Weave or Universal using Unearth (I had been laboring under the misconception that she could). As such, the trick that she does in the middle can&#39;t happen with her. However, there IS a way to get around this: Niffer. So, make the following changes to the deck list:<br />
<br />
-Swap Niffer for Gia.<br />
-Drop the Books of Ages for one more Ritual Spear and one more Warrada&#39;s Ring.<br />
<br />
I apologize for the inconvenience. If you have previously reviewed this deck, please read the new, revised strategy and tell me what you think. Thank you for your time.<br />
END EDIT INFO*** <br />
<br /><br />
<br />
Anyway, with that said, the idea behind this deck is to essentially take the dirty tricks that video game bosses just love use on you, and make a deck out of them.<br />
<br />
Anyway, the first and most important Magi is Korremar. Many nasty bosses keep some incredibly unpleasant status effect on you for the entire battle... I&#39;d say reducing your hand to one card per turn would qualify. If you want to know what to do with Korremar in-depth, read my "The Decisive Battle" deck strategy. Basically, use Mind Shock every turn, and draw cards other ways to have a massive card advantage over your opponent. Korremar is more than capable of winning the game solo.<br />
<br />
The next Magi is Niffer, but not for long. You know the boss trick where you finally, FINALLY kill the boss, but he turns around and revives himself before you even have a chance to heal? That&#39;s what Niffer does! You should have drawn a LOT of cards with Korremar, using Warrada&#39;s Ring, Book of Ages, Dream Rift, Chaos Plith, and the like. You MUST, I repeat, MUST have drawn a Ritual Spear, and you MUST have an Abwyn&#39;s Quill in your hand as well. Name Niffer&#39;s other region to be Weave. Play the Ritual Spear and the Abwyn&#39;s Quill. Use the Ritual Spear, but Overwrite it to say "Choose any one of your defeated Kybar&#39;s Teeth or CORE (instead of Weave) Magi...", and revive Korremar! Heeeeeeee&#39;s baaaaaaaaaack! Just use the streategy from when he WASN&#39;T a zombie, and whup up on your exhausted opponent.<br />
<br />
OK, so they killed Korremar twice. You know that nasty, NASTY tactic used by far too many bosses, that when you nearly kill them, they use a truly death-in-a-box attack, wiping you out if you haven&#39;t prepared for it? That&#39;s Harror&#39;s job. Harror is more than capable of taking out a Magi in one turn (Cataclysm + Dark Ayebaw = boom), so let her. It&#39;s nearly impossible for your opponent to have more than a single Magi left anyway, so you&#39;ll have probably won by now! If you haven&#39;t, you can throw in the towel, or you can skip the Cataclysm and just focus on her nasty Effect and nice starting cards to fight till the end. Your choice.<br />
<br />
As for clarification of some of the cards:<br />
<br />
Shryque is a safety net of sorts. If you can&#39;t draw any cards for some reason and thus have a low hand, play the Shryque(s) and lay your entire hend. So long as you keep up Mind Shock, each Shryque gains seven energy a turn (that&#39;s twenty-one energy every turn if you have all three out... nasty!). The better strategy is to draw as many cards as you can, rather than as few as you can, but they&#39;re there if you need them.<br />
<br />
Gia Pet, combined with Mind Shock, means that the opponent gets NO cards every turn, unless they draw them outside of their Draw Step (and then they still only get one). It&#39;s a nasty lock that&#39;s not hard to get! It doesn&#39;t affect you, either, since your Draw Step is essentially non-existant to begin with!<br />
<br />
Gloom combos with Korremar and Maelstrom and is a fairly easy way of killing a Magi outright. They&#39;ll have almost no cards in their hand anyway (probably none, if you play your cards right), so zap their energy with Maelstrom and their creatures with Gloom (no energy on their Magi and no hand means that they can&#39;t salvage their creatures). Think of it as the widespread-damage spell that so many bosses love. Magi KO.<br />
<br />
Warrada&#39;s Ring actually DOES allow you to draw a card at the end of your turn, since "the end of your turn" (which Warrada&#39;s Ring affects) and "your Draw Step" (which Mind Shock affects) are two different things.<br />
<br />
Beam of Light provides basic Relic control, and more importantly, it can get rid of Pure of Heart (which can really, REALLY hurt this deck). It&#39;s pretty much a utility card.<br />
<br />
Black Agovo comes in handy if your opponent starts hoarding cards in their hand. It&#39;s not hard to zap their hand completely.<br />
<br />
Oh, and if you were wondering, the title of this deck DOES mean something. "The Dreadful Fight" is the name of a song in Final Fantasy 4... it&#39;s played when fighting a particularly nasty team of bosses. (If you were wondering, "The Decisive Battle" is also a boss-battle song, this time from FF6).<br />
<br /><br />
